obo:ECO_0000314  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_758  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Authors used an antibody that specifically recognizes CRTC1 but not CRTC2 to study the localization of CRTC1 using spinning disk confocal microscopy. CRTC1 immunoreactivity was found in dendrites and spines, with 99% of PSD95-positive puncta containing CRTC1. This colocalization is activity regulated. Accordingly, CRTC1 was found in synaptoneurosome and PSD fractions.\nPull-down experiments using recombinant proteins show that CRTC1 binds to 14-3-3 epsilon, a protein found in dendritic spines, suggesting that the synaptic tethering of CRTC1 relies on the interaction with 14-3-3 epsilon. This interaction is also regulated by activity.. Experimental description: From M&M: Rodent hippocampal neurons were dissected from either newborn (P0) rat or mice.\n\nFrom Results:\n- Antibodies that specifically recognize CRTC1 were used to stain cultured rat hippocampal neurons (21 DIV).\n- To further examine the synaptic localization of CRTC1, we fractionated adult mouse brain into synaptoneurosome and postsynaptic density (PSD) fractions.\n- Specificity of the CRTC1 antibody. The coding sequence of mouse CRTC1 and CRTC2 were fused to the dendra2 photoconvertible protein in an expression vector driven by a CMV promoter\n\n14/6/2017 Pim\n- I have changed the species to rat based on preference for the rat IF data (supported by biochem.fract. data in mouse)." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0575-6950" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1585-539X" ;
        dc:date           "2017-08-10" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_758" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

<http://identifiers.org/rgd/1589158>
